<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8" standalone="yes"?><rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title>emsenn.net</title><link>https://emsenn.net/library/tech/domains/computing/domains/artificial-intelligence/domains/software/</link><description>Recent content on emsenn.net</description><generator>Hugo</generator><language>en-us</language><lastBuildDate>Sun, 08 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000</lastBuildDate><atom:link href="https://emsenn.net/library/tech/domains/computing/domains/artificial-intelligence/domains/software/index.xml" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"/><item><title>llama.cpp</title><link>https://emsenn.net/library/tech/domains/computing/domains/artificial-intelligence/domains/software/llama-cpp/</link><pubDate>Sun, 08 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://emsenn.net/library/tech/domains/computing/domains/artificial-intelligence/domains/software/llama-cpp/</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;llama.cpp&lt;/strong&gt; is an open-source C/C++ implementation of &lt;a href="../topics/on-device-inference/terms/large-language-model.md" class="link-internal"&gt;large language model&lt;/a&gt; inference, originally built for Meta&amp;rsquo;s &lt;a href="../topics/on-device-inference/terms/llama.md" class="link-internal"&gt;Llama&lt;/a&gt; models but now supporting most open-weight model architectures. It is the inference engine underneath &lt;a href="ollama/index.md" class="link-internal"&gt;Ollama&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;llama.cpp was created to run LLMs on consumer hardware — particularly CPUs — without requiring Python, CUDA, or other heavy dependencies. It reads models in &lt;a href="../topics/on-device-inference/terms/gguf.md" class="link-internal"&gt;GGUF&lt;/a&gt; format and supports &lt;a href="../topics/on-device-inference/terms/quantization.md" class="link-internal"&gt;quantization&lt;/a&gt; from 2-bit to 8-bit, making it possible to run 7B-parameter models on machines with 8 GB of RAM.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item></channel></rss>